It's about reviewing, getting
exposed to the English language.

246
00:12:20.130 --> 00:12:21.700
Rule number seven.

247
00:12:21.730 --> 00:12:26.100
"Just because you understand everything
doesn't mean it's too easy."

248
00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:30.500
I've said this many times already,
and it's so true, okay?

249
00:12:30.530 --> 00:12:33.100
Advanced English is bullshit.

250
00:12:33.130 --> 00:12:37.500
And now this is going to be very
controversial to a lot of people.

251
00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:40.500
And advanced English classes is basically

252
00:12:40.530 --> 00:12:44.940
an invention by universities and English
teachers to make more money.

253
00:12:44.970 --> 00:12:48.460
You do not need advanced English classes.

254
00:12:48.490 --> 00:12:50.300
Let me explain to you why,

255
00:12:50.329 --> 00:12:52.988
I'm gonna give you the
scientific definition

256
00:12:53.188 --> 00:12:54.620
of language learning, okay?

257
00:12:54.650 --> 00:12:56.980
And you hear how passionate
I am about this.

258
00:12:57.010 --> 00:12:59.643
It's because so few people
really understand this,

259
00:12:59.657 --> 00:13:03.960
and so they waste months
and years learning English that if they

260
00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:06.780
only knew this, they could
learn so much faster.

261
00:13:06.800 --> 00:13:08.940
Okay?
So listen to this.

262
00:13:11.290 --> 00:13:18.100
We learn languages, we acquire languages
by consuming i + 1 messages,

263
00:13:18.130 --> 00:13:23.100
where "i" is what you already know

264
00:13:23.130 --> 00:13:28.260
and 1 is a single unknown word
or grammar structure, okay?

265
00:13:28.290 --> 00:13:31.500
That's a scientific definition
of language learning, okay?

266
00:13:31.530 --> 00:13:34.460
The simple explanation is we learn a new

267
00:13:34.490 --> 00:13:41.460
word by hearing it in a sentence where we
already know all the other words, okay?

268
00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:43.380
So if you think about what you're doing

269
00:13:43.410 --> 00:13:48.020
in the RAIO App, you see an entire
phrase, you don't know it.

270
00:13:48.050 --> 00:13:50.420
You see the meaning in your language,

271
00:13:50.450 --> 00:13:54.180
and you can be like, "okay,
this is what it means."

272
00:13:54.210 --> 00:13:55.380
You swipe left.

273
00:13:55.410 --> 00:13:57.260
You get to see that phrase again.

274
00:13:57.290 --> 00:13:59.060
Now you know a little bit more.

275
00:13:59.080 --> 00:14:01.300
Now it's a little bit more comprehensible.

276
00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:02.540
Now you know a little bit more

277
00:14:02.560 --> 00:14:06.300
of the words inside of it, but it's still
a left swipe because you didn't know it

278
00:14:06.330 --> 00:14:08.620
fast and completely.
It comes up again.

279
00:14:08.650 --> 00:14:11.580
You see it again, and now you
know more and more and more.

280
00:14:11.610 --> 00:14:13.580
And the more you expose yourself

281
00:14:13.610 --> 00:14:19.220
to messages that you understand,
the more you are acquiring language,

282
00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:23.660
the more you are burning that vocabulary
and grammar structures into your brain,

283
00:14:23.690 --> 00:14:27.780
in the longterm memory,
which is the cause of language learning,

284
00:14:27.810 --> 00:14:31.260
which eventually allows
you to speak, okay?

285
00:14:31.290 --> 00:14:36.580
But input creates output,
and it takes time, okay?

286
00:14:36.610 --> 00:14:40.320
And remember, the stories will
increase in difficulty, okay?

287
00:14:40.350 --> 00:14:44.620
So right now in chapter one,
the sentences are very short, right?

288
00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:47.300
Three, four, five words
in each sentence, right?

289
00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:51.940
And the questions in the interactive
versions are yes or no questions, okay?

290
00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:55.540
I'm just asking you to say "yes" or "no".
Very easy.

291
00:14:55.570 --> 00:14:58.780
In the next chapter,
the sentences will be longer.

292
00:14:58.810 --> 00:15:02.500
We will use more advanced grammar
