308
00:15:45.450 --> 00:15:50.740
have more new vocabulary,
and be in more different time tenses.

309
00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:52.600
And the answers that you will have to give

310
00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:55.460
in the interactive version is
gonna be a one-word answer.

311
00:15:55.480 --> 00:15:56.900
So I'm gonna ask you a question.

312
00:15:56.930 --> 00:15:58.540
Let's say I say the same thing.

313
00:15:58.570 --> 00:16:02.260
"My sister's name is Linda,
and my nephew's name is Benjamin."

314
00:16:02.290 --> 00:16:05.818
"What's my sister's name?"

315
00:16:06.018 --> 00:16:06.700
- Linda.

316
00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:09.414
"What's my nephew's name?"

317
00:16:09.614 --> 00:16:10.420
- Benjamin.

318
00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:12.500
Correct.
So you have to actually respond

319
00:16:12.530 --> 00:16:16.620
with a word, and you're not going
to get any options. In chapter four,

320
00:16:16.650 --> 00:16:20.100
it's going to be even longer sentences,
more advanced sentences.

321
00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:23.180
The most advanced or hard grammar

322
00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:25.660
that exists is going
to be in chapter four.

323
00:16:25.680 --> 00:16:27.240
And the answers that you're gonna give

324
00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:31.180
in the interactive version are gonna be
full, complete sentences, right?

325
00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:35.060
And you see how the stories are
increasing in difficulty, all right?

326
00:16:35.080 --> 00:16:38.580
So you don't need advanced
English classes, okay?

327
00:16:38.610 --> 00:16:45.220
You just need to consume language that are
more and more and more complex and contain

328
00:16:45.250 --> 00:16:48.780
more stuff, that contain
more of these things.

329
00:16:48.810 --> 00:16:49.580
Okay?

330
00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:51.780
If this is a little
bit hard to understandm

331
00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:52.440
don't worry about it.

332
00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:56.020
You don't need to understand
perfectly the science, right?

333
00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:58.100
But just have that in mind.

334
00:16:58.130 --> 00:17:00.160
We learn a new word by hearing it

335
00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:03.740
in a sentence where we already
know all the other words, okay?

336
00:17:03.770 --> 00:17:07.940
We don't learn a new word
by reading it in a list, okay?

337
00:17:07.970 --> 00:17:09.500
Or someone telling us it.

338
00:17:09.530 --> 00:17:15.250
We need to hear that word in sentences
hundreds of times to be able to learn it.

339
00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:19.250
And that is exactly what you're
doing in this course, okay?

340
00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:24.530
Rule number eight, respond in your
language for as long as you need.

341
00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:26.380
This is also a bit controversial because

342
00:17:26.410 --> 00:17:29.660
a lot of people will tell you,
"no, you need to force speaking."

343
00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:32.180
"You need to talk a lot."
"Talk, talk, talk, talk, talk."

344
00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:33.620
Really force it, right?

345
00:17:33.650 --> 00:17:36.244
"Step out of your comfort zone!"

346
00:17:36.444 --> 00:17:38.250
To some degree,
that's correct.

347
00:17:38.280 --> 00:17:41.220
But you may respond in your own language
for as long as you need,

348
00:17:41.250 --> 00:17:45.460
because you should not
focus on speaking accuracy,

349
00:17:45.490 --> 00:17:51.010
but conversation fluency, because
what is the cause of language learning?

350
00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:51.684
Input.

351
00:17:51.884 --> 00:17:52.220
Okay?

352
00:17:52.250 --> 00:17:57.700
And if you have fluency in conversations,
you will get more input, okay?

353
00:17:57.730 --> 00:18:00.140
And so if you need to respond in your own

354
00:18:00.170 --> 00:18:03.940
language because you don't know how
to respond in English, do that.

355
00:18:03.960 --> 00:18:05.660
Keep the fluency in conversations.

356
00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:07.740
Don't let the conversation get stuck.

357
00:18:07.770 --> 00:18:11.290
It's not about speaking accuracy.

358
00:18:11.320 --> 00:18:14.010
Your speaking accuracy will improve

359
00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:17.460
with more input and more
expansion of a vocabulary.

360
00:18:17.490 --> 00:18:20.570
The more you consume,
the better the accuracy will be.

361
00:18:20.600 --> 00:18:22.320
So focus on conversation fluency.

362
00:18:22.350 --> 00:18:26.530
If you want to respond in your own
language, do that for as long as you need.

363
00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:29.420
Language learning should
never be stressful.

364
00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:31.500
It's actually scientifically proven

365
00:18:31.530 --> 00:18:35.220
that if you're stressed when
learning a language, you learn less.

366
00:18:35.250 --> 00:18:35.810
Okay?

367
00:18:35.840 --> 00:18:40.380
So the whole thing about going out and be
really uncomfortable and forcing speaking

368
00:18:40.410 --> 00:18:46.500
is just a terrible tip because stress
completely kills learning, okay?

369
00:18:46.530 --> 00:18:47.420
So relax.

370
00:18:47.450 --> 00:18:50.770
Respond in your own language
for as long as you need.

371
00:18:50.800 --> 00:18:51.620
Okay?

372
00:18:51.650 --> 00:18:56.530
Rule number nine, don't ask
people to correct you.

373
00:18:56.560 --> 00:18:58.200
This is extremely controversial.

374
00:18:58.230 --> 00:19:01.220
I know a lot of you guys will say,
"Kale, are you crazy?"

375
00:19:01.240 --> 00:19:04.010
"What are you talking about?
I love when people correct me."

376
00:19:04.040 --> 00:19:06.770
"I want people to correct
me so I can improve."

377
00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:08.810
No, you don't.

378
00:19:08.840 --> 00:19:11.460
According to language learning science,

379
00:19:11.490 --> 00:19:15.140
getting corrected feels like
learning, but it isn't, okay?

380
00:19:15.170 --> 00:19:18.860
It feels like learning because
you're being corrected on the spot.

381
00:19:18.890 --> 00:19:22.010
Now, why isn't a correction learning?

382
00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:29.660
Because if you say,
for example, "he run."

383
00:19:29.690 --> 00:19:35.290
You say "he run" instead of "he runs".

384
00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:40.180
This is correct, and this is incorrect.

385
00:19:40.210 --> 00:19:44.620
If you say this and someone corrects you
and says, "no, you shouldn't say that."

386
00:19:44.650 --> 00:19:46.250
"You say 'he runs.'"

387
00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:51.250
That is one piece of exposure,
one point of input.

388
00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:54.570
You need hundreds of points of input.

389
00:19:54.600 --> 00:19:59.500
You need to expose yourself
to "he runs", "she cooks",

390
00:19:59.530 --> 00:20:03.770
"it rains", hundreds of times

391
00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:06.330
in order for you to learn this grammatical

392
00:20:06.360 --> 00:20:09.250
rule here, you need to expose
yourself hundreds of times.

393
00:20:09.280 --> 00:20:12.250
Just getting corrected once
does not do that for you.

394
00:20:12.280 --> 00:20:15.140
It feels like learning
in the moment, but it is not.

395
00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:15.620
Okay?

396
00:20:15.650 --> 00:20:19.950
So if someone is correcting
you, if you work or live

397
00:20:20.150 --> 00:20:24.570
with native English speakers,

398
00:20:24.600 --> 00:20:28.740
if you have a native English speaking
partner that is correcting you all

399
00:20:28.770 --> 00:20:32.740
the time, tell them to stop
and tell them to do this instead.

400
00:20:32.770 --> 00:20:38.980
Rather than correcting
one word, tell them to just repeat what

401
00:20:39.010 --> 00:20:42.900
you said, the full sentence,
but in the correct way.

402
00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:48.530
So if you said, "he run really fast".

403
00:20:48.560 --> 00:20:52.593
If you say this,
your friend shouldn't say,

404
00:20:52.793 --> 00:20:55.220
"No, no. You don't say 'he run'.
You say 'he runs'."

405
00:20:55.250 --> 00:20:56.102
No, no.

406
00:20:56.302 --> 00:21:01.090
Tell him to say,
"Ah, he 'runs' really fast."

407
00:21:01.120 --> 00:21:07.810
Repeat the full answer in the correct way,
exactly as we teach our children, right?

408
00:21:07.840 --> 00:21:10.220
That is exactly how we
teach children, right?

409
00:21:10.250 --> 00:21:12.290
We don't say "no, no,
that's not how you say that."

410
00:21:12.320 --> 00:21:14.900
We just repeat what they
said in the correct way.

411
00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:16.250
That's how you get corrected.

412
00:21:16.280 --> 00:21:18.500
So don't ask people to correct you.

413
00:21:18.530 --> 00:21:21.460
Just ask them to repeat what
you said in the correct way.

414
00:21:22.560 --> 00:21:23.994
Rule number ten,

415
00:21:24.194 --> 00:21:26.770
"Be patient, languages don't have an end."

416
00:21:26.800 --> 00:21:28.530
We've talked about this before, right?

417
00:21:28.560 --> 00:21:34.900
To lose patience is to lose the battle,
which the great Gandhi said, okay?

418
00:21:34.920 --> 00:21:36.660
Right?
Languages don't have an end.

419
00:21:36.680 --> 00:21:37.160
You know that

420
00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:39.050
there are many different
milestones, right?

421
00:21:39.080 --> 00:21:40.940
Remember the RAIO milestones, okay?

422
00:21:40.960 --> 00:21:42.010
Conversationally fluemt

423
00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:44.770
and is when you can hold
conversations.

424
00:21:44.800 --> 00:21:46.770
I don't know why this is all in Spanish.

425
00:21:46.800 --> 00:21:49.200
It should be in English.

426
00:21:49.320 --> 00:21:51.180
Have a 30 minutes conversation.

427
00:21:56.680 --> 00:21:59.050
There are different milestones, right?

428
00:21:59.080 --> 00:22:08.000
So when you can have a 30 minutes
